accesses.location: A gravel boat access is located at the southeast end of the lake.  Lake County Rd. #7 runs along the length of the east shore and there are many sites for shore fishing.

surveys.narrative: High densities of Splake are being maintained through annual stocking of fall fingerlings. The gillnet catch of 8.0/lift represents a small decline from historic levels, however Splake numbers are sufficient to sustain the fishery. No Splake over 12 inches were taken, however anglers commonly catch Splake in the 12 to 14 inch range. Recent assessments have shown a decline in gillnet catches of Rainbow Trout. No Rainbow Trout were taken in gillnets during this survey, and only 2 were captured in trapnets. A more effective sampling method may have to be found as anglers are catching Rainbow Trout but fisheries sampling gear is not.

A zooplankton survey was performed in August 2015 by making three vertical hauls with a 45 cm diameter net made of 80 micron mesh over the deepest portion of the lake. The purpose was to gather baseline information about zooplankton species present, relative densities, and to check for the potential presence of zebra mussels, spiny water flea, or other aquatic invasive species. No aquatic invasive species were identified.

Continue the Lake Trout stocking on an annual basis for 4 years. Echo Lake is one of only three Lake Trout lakes in the Finland Area below the BWCAW unit. Assessment net in three years to monitor trout and to check on a possible Yellow Perch build-up.

Echo Lake is 42 acres, has a maximum depth of 61 feet, and is located approximately 16 miles northeast of Finland, MN. There is a gravel back-in access on the southeast side of the lake off of Lake County Road #7. There are numerous shore fishing spots along the side of Lake County Road #7.

The 2018 standard survey was conducted to monitor the fish community in Echo Lake and continue to evaluate the trout stocking for the lake. Echo Lake is stocked annually with 3,000 Rainbow Trout yearlings in the spring. The Rainbow Trout gill net catch was slightly above average compared to similar lakes in the area. The trap net catch of Rainbow Trout was also above average for the area. The average size of Rainbow Trout was 12.3 inches and 0.7 pounds. The largest Rainbow Trout was 16.1 inches. Three year classes were seen and indicate Rainbow Trout are able to survive in Echo Lake.

Annual fall stocking of 2,500 Splake fingerlings maintain a Splake population in Echo Lake. The Splake gill net catch was lower than average and one of the lowest seen in the lake. However, the trap net catch for Splake was well above average and one of the highest seen in the lake. The average size was 12.5 inches and 0.7 pounds. The largest fish seen was 16.8 inches. Splake are able to survive and grow in Echo Lake as three year classes were sampled.

White Sucker were also sampled with the survey nets have been caught in every survey since 1987 but generally at low numbers.

Echo Lake is one of the better "designated stream trout" lakes in the Finland area. Anglers tend to target the lake in the early spring and late fall for open water fishing although fish can be caught throughout the summer. The winter trout season is another great time to target Rainbow Trout and Splake on Echo Lake and the angling pressure is usually high.

A survey was completed in August 2019 to monitor the zooplankton community in Echo Lake. Samples were analyzed to provide baseline information on the zooplankton community composition and abundance and to determine if any aquatic invasive species have become established in the lake.

Echo Lake was selected for annual zooplankton sampling in 2015 because it is considered to be at moderate risk of infestation compared to other area lakes. Sampling in 2019 consisted of three vertical plankton tows made with a 50 centimeter diameter net with 80 micron mesh from a depth of 50 feet. Zooplankton community composition was similar to previous surveys completed on the lake. No aquatic invasive species have been sampled since monitoring began.

Echo Lake can be classified as a Lake Trout - Smallmouth Bass lake. There appears to be a good "native" population of Lake Trout. All sizes were well represented in the test net catches. Ecologically a Lake Trout - Smallmouth Bass lake, Echo Lake has a good population of both. The bass have become established through stocking. If Rainbow Trout populations are to exist in this lake, they must be maintained by stocking. Some measure of control over the Smalllmouth Bass should be made to improve for the trout. There does not seem to be enough utilization of the trout at the present time.

Rainbow trout provide good angling opportunities on Echo Lake. Three thousand rainbow trout yearlings are stocked each spring and average about 1/3 pound when stocked. The 2008 assessment sampled low numbers of rainbow trout, not unusual, rainbow trout are net-shy and the population difficult to assess. The splake population in Echo Lake is maintained through annual stocking of 2,500 splake fingerlings in the fall. Netting results indicate an above average population of splake with fish up to 15 inches sampled. Brook trout are present in low numbers in Echo Lake; there has been no recent brook trout stocking, so the fish sampled in 2008 are from a self-sustaining population. Brook trout up to 10.7 inches were sampled in the 2008 assessment.

A survey was performed on August 15, 2017 to gather baseline information about the zooplankton community and to check for the presence of zebra mussels, spiny water flea, or other aquatic invasive species. Sampling consisted of three vertical hauls using a 50 cm diameter net with 80 micron mesh made over the deepest part of the lake. No aquatic invasive species were sampled.

A survey was performed on August 17, 2018 to gather baseline information about the zooplankton community and to check for the presence of zebra mussels, spiny water flea, or other aquatic invasive species. Sampling consisted of three vertical hauls with a 50 cm diameter net with 80 micron mesh made over the deepest part of the lake. No aquatic invasive species were sampled.

The Rainbow Trout catch in gillnets was nearly twice the local average. Brook Trout were equal to the local average for both gillnet and trapnet. The Brook Trout were from the initial stocking of about 4200 yearlings in 1986. The Lake Trout catch in gillnets was about 2 times the local average, however Lake Trout trout stocking has been discontinued. The Splake catch in gillnets continues to be in excess of 8.5/lift. White Sucker remain at low numbers. The presence of Atlantic Salmon is believed to be the result of an accidental mixing with Rainbow Trout at a state operated rearing facility.

Echo Lake is a designated trout lake located in Lake County approximately 16 miles northeast of Finland. There is a public access with earthen ramp suitable for smaller boats on the south side of the lake as well as several places to fish from shore along Lake County Road 7. The lake is stocked with yearling Rainbow Trout each spring and fall to provide fish for the summer and winter angling seasons. In addition, fingerling Splake are stocked each fall that live in the lake from year to year to provide additional angling opportunities.

The 2023 fisheries survey sampled low numbers of Rainbow Trout that were stocked in spring based on their size. The survey occurred toward the end of the summer season when most harvest had taken place and before fall yearling stocking meant to supplement the population for the winter fishery. The few Rainbow Trout caught does confirm that not all the fish stocked in spring are harvested by anglers during the summer.

Splake catch was the highest to date for the lake, but only a few fish were longer than fourteen inches. These results are similar to previous surveys of the lake that found Splake regularly survive in the lake for multiple years, but seldom reach larger sizes compared to other stream trout lakes in the area.

Echo Lake is a popular trout lake and receives a good amount of angling effort in summer and winter. Annual stocking with Rainbow Trout and Splake will continue into the future to provide quality fishing opportunities for anglers.

Continue management with Splake and Rainbow Trout. Although Rainbow Trout did not appear in the test nets anglers have been catching them. Assessment netting will be crried out during late May of 1984 in an attempt to better monitor the Rainbow Trout population in this clear water lake. A stocking of 4000 Lake Trout will be made in 1983 to re-establish Lake Trout which this lake provided in the past. Lake Trout lakes are rare outside the BWCAW in the Finland Area.

Splake were present in average numbers in 2002, compared to other stream trout lakes in the area. Most were less than 12 inches in length. Brook trout were also present, probably as a result of natural reproduction. It was difficult to tell the brook trout and splake apart in the field, so in this report all have been listed as splake. Echo Lake was found to support a splake (and brook trout) population of between 187 and 1,148 fish (probably about 470 fish).Few rainbow trout were taken in gill nets or trap nets, but electrofishing indicated that fairly high numbers of 8 to 10 inch fish from the 2002 stocking were present.

Echo Lake is a "Designated Stream Trout Lake" that is stocked annually with yearling rainbow trout and fingerling splake. The lake is open to angling during the stream trout season (lakes) only and possessing minnows or using them for bait on designated stream trout lakes is prohibited. Only one line is permitted at any time. All stream trout must have head, tail, fins and skin intact when being transported. There is a back down gravel ramp on the south end of the lake and the lake is easily accessible from Lake County Road #7 for shore fishing. Echo Lake is one of the more popular stream trout lakes in the Finland area.The splake catch in 2005 was in the normal range compared to other lakes in this class, but was lower than past catches in this lake. This lake is usually a decent lake for catching splake, especially during the winter trout season. Splake in this assessment had a mean length of 9.2 inches with a maximum of 12.4 inches. Splake caught by anglers during the winter trout season may be somewhat larger. Most of the splake caught by anglers are from 1-3 years old. Due to natural mortality and angler harvest not many splake survive to 4 years in this lake.Rainbow trout were collected in fairly low number in this assessment and the size ranged from 12.8 inches to 14.0 inches. All the rainbow trout in this assessment were age-2 fish. Age-1 year-class (8-10 inch) fish had not been stocked yet at the time of the assessment, and due to natural mortality and angler harvest few rainbow trout survive to reach age 2 or older.

Echo Lake is a 42.1 acre lake in the Superior National Forest. The maximum depth is 61 feet and it has light green algae stained water. The lake is located 13 miles northeast of Finland. Access is a gravel ramp off of Lake County Highway #7 along the southeast shore.

Cold water temperatures and good dissolved oxygen levels are essential for trout growth and survival. To assess these important criteria, six automatic temperature loggers were deployed at the deepest location in the lake, they were suspended at depths of 10, 15, 20, 25, 30, and 35 feet on May 23, 2018. Dissolved oxygen checks were conducted throughout the summer at the same location. During the temperature and oxygen test performed on September 20 the crew was not able to locate the underwater buoys marking the logger chain. Attempts made to recover the gear were unsuccessful and it is assumed that the logger chain was tampered with and either lost or stolen. Echo Lake is stocked annually with Rainbow Trout yearlings, Splake fingerlings and occasionally Rainbow Trout brood stock when available.

The results of the investigation indicate that during the summer of 2018, Echo Lake maintained sufficient oxygen and thermal habitat for the survival of stream trout. These parameters will continue to be carefully monitored in future investigations to check the suitability of Echo Lake for trout stocking.

A zooplankton survey was performed on August 17, 2016 by making three vertical hauls with a 50 cm diameter net made of 80 micron mesh over the deep hole in the lake. The purpose was to gather baseline information about zooplankton species present, density and to check for the presence of zebra mussels, spiny water flea or other aquatic invasive species. No aquatic invasive species were identified.

Echo Lake is a Designated Trout Lake located on a maintained gravel road 15 miles northeast of Finland, Minnesota. Angling is allowed during the open trout season only, and the possession and use of live minnows is prohibited. A gravel ramp on the south end of the lake provides access to watercraft, and shorefishing is accessible from Lake County Road #7 on the east side of the lake. The gamefish population is comprised primarily of splake and rainbow trout which are stocked annually. There is also a remnant population of lake trout and brook trout. Test nets in 1997 indicate splake numbers are high when compared to other splake lakes in the Finland Management Area. Splake up to 13.5 inches were observed, but the most common size sampled was from 10 inches to 12 inches. Rainbow trout were sampled in low numbers, however this species has traditionally been difficult to sample with standard netting gear. These results should not discourage anglers from pursuing rainbow trout as good fishing reports are not uncommon. The rainbow trout in test nets in 1997 ranged in size from 12.4 inches to 15.3 inches. Although lake trout have not been stocked since 1985 Echo Lake does support a very small population, but they are not commonly caught by anglers. The lone lake trout sampled in 1997 was 13.6 pounds. Echo Lake is no longer managed for brook trout. The last stocking in 1996 is providing a low population to anglers. As these brook trout complete their life cycle in one or two years none will be present in the lake.

Echo Lake is a 42.1 acre "Designated Stream Trout Lake" with a maximum depth of 61 feet. Much of the eastern shore is near Lake County Road #7, allowing for ample shore fishing. The south end of the lake has a gravel back-in access off of Lake County Road #7. The lake stocked with three thousand Rainbow Trout yearlings each spring. The yearlings average around 1/3 pound when stocked. The 2013 assessment sampled higher than normal numbers of Rainbow Trout ranging in size from 11.0 to 17.1 inches at capture and had an average weight of 0.73 pounds. Rainbow Trout provide good open water angling opportunities. Fall stocking of 2,500 Splake fingerlings maintains a Splake population in the lake. The 2013 assessment captured Splake ranging from 5.7 to 20.1 inches and weighed an average of 0.37 pounds. The Splake numbers were above average for similar lakes in the area. Splake provide excellent angling opportunities during the winter trout season on Echo Lake. White Suckers are also present in low numbers in Echo Lake. Anglers tend to target Echo Lake in the early spring and late fall for open water fishing and the first few weeks of the winter trout season.
